            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-11-02T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-11-02T03:00:00-05:00" n="692" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d692">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">121.67/11–248: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-11-02T16:00:00+08:00">November 2, 1948—4 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 2—4:38 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2292. Deptel 1843, 1st, 1 [<hi rend="italic">3</hi>] p. m., repeated Moscow 1282.
                    Local Soviet Consulate advises steamer available about November 15 for
                    Vladivostok. Koval and Bernhardt<note n="21" xml:id="d692fn21">John Koval and
                        Matthias R. Bernhardt, respectively, chosen to go as couriers to
                        Dairen.</note> visas requested, personal data <pb facs="0808" n="798" xml:id="pg_798"/> at Embassy Moscow. Trip feasible if Soviet Foreign Office
                    authorizes Soviet Consulate Shanghai issue visas by November 10.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 2292; repeated Moscow 33, Dairen 87, pouched Nanking 1735.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cabot</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
